post_text:
Attached is a revised 2020-21 school calendar approved by the School Board at their August 20, 2020 meeting. These changes were made in consideration of the altered school schedule WPPS will follow during the first instructional grading period. The four changes include:

October 12 - now becomes a full instructional day rather than an early release for Parent/Teacher Conferences
October 30 - now becomes a full instructional day rather than early release for Teacher Professional Learning
November 6 - now becomes the end of the first grading period versus November 10 (First grading period will have 43 days)
November 9 - now becomes the beginning of the second grading period (Second marking period will have 46 days)

post_text: West Point Public Schools recognizes that this has been a very challenging time for many of our students, families, and the community as a whole. We also recognize the strength that can come from a community uniting to provide for their own. Through September 12, 2020, WPPS is hosting an online school supply drive to ensure that every student and teacher in our schools have what they need to be successful in this unique academic year. Please consider donating and know that any contribution will make a positive difference for students in grades PK-12. More information can be found by visiting https://yougivegoods.com/drive-wpps.

post_text:
Free and Reduced Meal Applications are now available online.
We encourage you to complete an application if you believe your family may qualify for these benefits. If your family received these benefits in the past and have not received a letter stating that your children are prequalified for this school year, please visit www.myschoolapps.com or visit the school website at www.wpschools.net to access the online application. If you require a paper application, please contact Misty Osborne at mosborne@wpschools.net. You will be notified by mail of your child's status.

Only complete one application per family. The information you give will be used to determine or prove your child's eligibility for free or reduced-priced meals. This information may also be used for other state or federally funded school benefits.

We encourage you to submit your meal application as soon as possible.

post_text:
Class of 2020 Parade Route

We have received questions about the route that the Class of 2020 Parade will follow this Friday starting at 6:30 p.m. Led by the Town of West Point Police, the parade will leave the high school parking lot and turn left onto Mattaponi Ave. Cross Thompson Ave. and make a right onto Chelsea Rd. At Rte. 33, make a right and then a left onto Lee St. At 2nd St., make a right and then a right onto Main St. At the light, cross Rte. 33 and proceed on King William Ave. and make a right on Thompson Ave. and head back to the high school parking lot.
The parade will be held rain or shine, except if there is lightning in the area. Make sure to get your blue or orange light bulbs at Horn's Ace Hardware to show your support for this special group of seniors!

post_text:
A fast-moving winter weather event is moving through our area. Forecasts indicate below freezing temperatures overnight and into the late morning. This means the potential exists for ice forming on any standing water on roadways, sidewalks and parking lots. Our Operations Team has already pre-treated division sidewalks and they will monitor conditions overnight.

NO DECISION will be made until tomorrow morning regarding the need for a possible delayed school opening or closure. Any changes to the normal school schedule will be communicated via the SchoolMessenger calling system by 6:15 a.m. If there is no call/email, then there is no change and schools will open on their regular schedule.
As always, the safety of our students and staff is our top priority.

post_text: In the spirit of West Point's Food Trucks by the River, WPES 5th grade students collaborated to create food truck businesses! They combined their math, persuasive writing, and creative thinking skills in order to compete with other "businesses" to attract the most sales. Visiting patrons (Town of West Point officials, School Administrators, 5th-grade peers, 3rd Grade, and 1st Grade) were given "money" to spend at their favorite establishments. 5th Grade students took orders, calculated totals, and made change. At the end of the event, students calculated their total sales and reflected on what worked and didn't work with their business plans. Swimming Seafood took the lead with $321 in sales!

post_text: Mrs. Gresham has been teaching her first-grade students about simple machines and wanted to take it even further! After studying how simple machines can be combined to perform a task (think Rube Goldberg!), her students had many ideas! The inventive first graders came up with a simple task they would like help with (like feeding the cat, kicking a ball, or pouring a drink). They then collaborated with Mrs. Hixenbaugh’s fifth-grade class to help make their ideas come to life! Both grade levels are looking forward to seeing the finished products in action!

shared_text:
West Point High School Athletics
November 6, 2019 at 11:46 PM ·

Today's Region Cross Country Meet at Eastern State went AMAZING!

West Point Girls finished 1st and are Region 1A Champions

Girls All-Region runners
Eliza Diggs finished 4th
Sophia Diggs finished 5th
Kylie Martin finished 8th
Avery Jenkins finished 11th
Jordan Roane finished 13th

West Point Boys finished 3rd

Boys All-Region
Andrew Choate finished 5th

To our knowledge, this is the first time both the Boys and Girls Cross Country teams have qualified for the state meet. Way to go ladies and gentlemen and congrats to coaches Young, McCallister and Mollenhour!

Based on the updated weather forecast that now includes West Point in a Tropical Storm Warning and the strong potential for power outages, West Point Public Schools will be closed on Friday, September 6, 2019. As always, our goal is to put safety first and ensure that our students and staff have optimal conditions in which to learn and work.

The home volleyball game scheduled for this evening will go on as planned and Friday night's home football game is now rescheduled at home on Monday, September 9th at 6:00 pm.
text:
Based on the updated weather forecast that now includes West Point in a Tropical Storm Warning and the strong potential for power outages, West Point Public Schools will be closed on Friday, September 6, 2019. As always, our goal is to put safety first and ensure that our students and staff have optimal conditions in which to learn and work.

The home volleyball game scheduled for this evening will go on as planned and Friday night's home football game is now rescheduled at home on Monday, September 9th at 6:00 pm.

post_text:
It was a great day for a track meet. Congratulations to our girls team champion Lady Pointers at today's 21st annual Pointer Invitational track & field meet.

Congratulations to our Pointers for picking up 10 gold medals in individual and relay events.

Catherine Bishop was the best of the best today taking home a gold medal for scoring the most points of all of the girls! Woohoo!

Congratulations to Jenna Kirkland. Her Discus throw of 117'2" breaks her own school record and breaks the Tidewater District and Region 1A records.

Big thanks to all of the volunteers that helped us pull off another great track meet!

post_text: We concluded the Kid's Heart Challenge, formerly known as Jump Rope for Heart, on March 22nd. The students at the elementary school learned about making heart healthy choices on the morning announcements from SCA members, practiced active lifestyles in P.E., and raised money for the American Heart Association online! The class who had the most students participate was Mrs. Ferguson's second grade class. As a school, we raised $2,754.00.

The class who had the most students participate was Mrs. Ferguson's second grade class. As a school, we raised $2,754.00.

post_text: Second graders at WPES traveled to Colonial Williamsburg to learn about growing up in Colonial Times. post_text: Robert Lawrence, Financial Advisor from Edward Jones Investments, met with WPES 5th Grade Stock Market Club teams to discuss their virtual portfolios. Students are currently competing against 86 other teams regionally, most of which are middle and high school aged students, through the Stock Market Game. By utilizing Mr. Lawrence’s suggestions, the four teams are currently placed at an impressive 8th, 9th, 15th, and 25th place.

post_text: Due to the uncertain weather forecast that puts West Point on the edge of the rain/ice/snow forecast and temperatures right at the freezing level, West Point Public Schools will operate on a two-hour delay Wednesday, February 20, 2019. This delay will allow time for the forecast to be confirmed and our staff to assess road conditions in the morning. If there is a need for additional changes to the schedule, we will notify you by 6:30 tomorrow morning.
